## 9. Security Architecture

### 9.1 Trust boundaries

- **Browser → Next.js server:** HTTPS only (Railway enforces this). All session validation happens server-side. Client-side role checks are UX only — not security.
- **Next.js server → PostgreSQL:** Internal Railway network. Connection string in environment variable only.
- **No browser-to-database path:** The browser never touches the database directly. All data access goes through Next.js server-side code.

### 9.2 Threat model (relevant threats at this scale)

| Threat | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| Credential stuffing / brute force | bcrypt slows hash comparison; Railway can add rate limiting at the edge if needed |
| Session hijacking | `httpOnly` + `Secure` cookie; 30-day TTL; NEXTAUTH_SECRET rotatable |
| Horizontal privilege escalation (staff accessing another program) | middleware.ts checks `session.programId === route [id]` on every request |
| Vertical privilege escalation (staff reaching admin routes) | middleware.ts role-to-route table; no role elevation path in the UI |
| SQL injection | Prisma parameterises all queries; no raw SQL in v1 |
| Plaintext password exposure | bcrypt only; never logged |

### 9.3 Out of scope

- MFA / 2FA (not in PRD)
- IP allowlisting (not warranted at this scale)
- Penetration testing (not warranted for a ~12-user internal tool)
- GDPR / PIPEDA compliance audit (noted as a future concern for a Canadian nonprofit but not in v1 scope)

