### 12.1 Environments

| Environment | Purpose | URL |
|---|---|---|
| Production | Live app used by the org | Railway-assigned domain (custom domain optional) |
| Development | Local developer machine | `localhost:3000` |

> ⚠️ **Needs input:** No staging environment has been defined. For a ~12-user internal tool, a staging environment is optional but recommended before deploying changes that touch the database schema.

### 12.2 Deployment process

1. Developer pushes to `main` branch on GitHub.
2. Railway detects the push and runs the build.
3. Build runs: `npx prisma migrate deploy && npm run build`.
4. On success, Railway swaps the running container. Zero-downtime on Railway's Hobby plan is not guaranteed — acceptable for this use case.
5. On failure, Railway keeps the previous container running.

### 12.3 Environment variables

Set in the Railway dashboard. Required variables listed in §7.4. No `.env` files are committed to the repository.

### 12.4 Database backups

Railway's PostgreSQL includes automated daily backups with a 7-day retention window on paid plans. Enable this before go-live. Document the restore procedure in a separate runbook — not in this document.

### 12.5 Migrations

Prisma migrations are version-controlled in `prisma/migrations/`. They run automatically on each deploy (`prisma migrate deploy`). The migration command is non-destructive — it applies only pending migrations and never drops columns that have data.

> Targets cannot be backdated to a period that already has entries (PRD §4, Flow D). This is enforced at the application layer; there is no database trigger enforcing it.

