### ADR-007 — API Routes for all mutations; Server Actions not used

**Decision:** All form submissions and data mutations use Next.js API Routes (under `app/api/`). Server Actions are not used anywhere in the codebase.

**Alternatives considered:**
- Server Actions for all mutations — rejected: Server Actions in Next.js 14 use an internal fetch mechanism that does not pass through `middleware.ts` in the same way as standard HTTP requests. A builder who implements mutations as Server Actions and assumes middleware provides role enforcement will have no protection on write operations. The failure is silent — no error, just missing enforcement.
- Server Actions with per-action session checks — rejected: this works, but it creates a second enforcement pattern alongside `middleware.ts`. Every new mutation would require the developer to remember to add the session check manually. One missed check = a privilege escalation bug. A single enforcement point is safer.

**Rationale:** API Routes go through `middleware.ts` reliably and consistently. The `/api/report/pdf` route already establishes this pattern. Extending it to all mutations keeps the security model simple: one enforcement point, one mechanism, no exceptions. The developer ergonomics tradeoff (API Routes require slightly more boilerplate than Server Actions) is worth it for correctness at this scale.

---

These are explicitly not being built. If this list shrinks, flag it as a scope change.

- **Background jobs or queues** — all operations are synchronous request/response. No worker processes.
- **Caching layer** — no Redis, no in-memory cache. All reads go to PostgreSQL. At ~12 users, this is not a performance concern.
- **Multi-tenancy** — single organisation, single instance. No `org_id` on any table.
- **External API integrations** — no calls to third-party services (CRM, Eventbrite, Google Sheets) in v1.
- **Realtime / WebSockets** — dashboard data is fetched on page load. No live updates.
- **Mobile native app** — web browser only.
- **AI-generated content** — ED Notes is a free-text field; no LLM calls in v1.
- **Audit log** — `entered_by`, `entered_at`, `updated_by`, `updated_at` on relevant tables provide a light audit trail. No dedicated audit log table or log shipping.

